      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 30446,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Ans. D) Transmitted in classical Mendelian fashion</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;\">&nbsp;</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option D:</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">The <strong>Mitochondrial genome</strong> of the <strong>mother</strong> is <strong>transferred </strong>to <strong>all of its offspring.</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Diseases due to mutation in mitochondrial genome:</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><ol style=\"list-style-type:decimal;\"><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">MELAS<strong> â€“ </strong>Mitochondrial Encephalopathy Lactic Acidosis and Stroke like episode</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Leigh Syndrome&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Leber Hereditary Optic Neuropathy</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">NARP Syndrome<strong>- </strong>Neuropathy, Ataxia, Retinitis Pigmentosa</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">MERRF<strong>- </strong>Myoclonic Epilepsy and Ragged Red Fibres in muscles</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">CPEO<strong>- </strong>Chronic Progressive External Ophthalmoplegia</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Kearns Sayre Syndrome</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Pearson Syndrome<strong>- </strong>Lactic Acidosis, Pancreatic Insufficiency, Pancytopenia</span></p></li></ol><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Explanation</u>:</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option A. Contains 37 genes</strong>: This is <strong>true</strong>. Human mitochondrial DNA contains 37 genes, encoding 13 proteins, 22 tRNAs, and 2 rRNAs.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option B. Transmitted from mother to offspring:</strong>&nbsp; This is true. Mitochondrial DNA is passed down from mothers to all of their children, both male and female.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option C. Causes Leber hereditary optic neuropathy</strong>: This is <strong>true</strong>. Mutations in mitochondrial DNA can cause Leber hereditary optic neuropathy, a condition that leads to vision loss.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Educational Objective:</u></strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/04/05/screenshot-2024-04-05-155701.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"1000\" height=\"672\"></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Ref</u>: Harper 30/e:&nbsp; p 378.</strong></span>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>",
