      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">During a grand rounds presentation on rare ophthalmological disorders, a case of a 25-year-old male with sudden bilateral vision loss, initially presenting as loss of central vision in the left eye followed by the right, is discussed. The patient has no significant medical history or risk factors, and ophthalmoscopic examination reveals characteristic findings. The diagnosis is Leber hereditary optic neuropathy (LHON). The attendees are asked to identify the incorrect statement about LHON?</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/04/18/screenshot-2024-04-18-130327.png\" style=\"height:152px; width:300px\" /></span></span></span></p>",
